s richly illustrates how hockey is played and experienced by First Nations peoples across Canada, both in isolated reserve communities and at tournaments that bring together participants from across the country. Robidoux&apos;s vivid description transports readers into the world of First Nations hockey, revealing it to be a highly social and at times even spiritual activity ripe with hidden layers of meaning that are often surprising to the outside observer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHockeyxSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aHockeyxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aHockeyxTournamentsxCanada. 0aHockeyxTournamentszCanada. 0aIndian hockey playersxSocial conditionsxCanada. 0aIndian hockey playerszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEthnic identityxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSportsxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSportszCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxEthnic identity. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Hockey.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266213140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662131423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662131.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK